%N A397411 Smallest number k such that bigomega(k+i) and omega(k+i), for i=0..n, but not for i=n+1, are both prime.
%C A397411 a(28) = 1356788893, a(29) = 6409098262. a(n) is nonprime. Let p be the largest prime < a(n). Let q be the smallest prime >= a(n). Then q - p >= n + 2. - _David A. Corneth_, Jun 24 2026
%e A397411 a(0) = 6 as both bigomega(6+0) = 2 and omega(6+0) = 2 are prime but not both bigomega(6+0+1) and omega(6+0+1) are prime. 6 is the smallest number having this property. - _David A. Corneth_, Jun 24 2026
%e A397411 a(1) = 14 as bigomega(14) = 2 and omega(14) = 2 are both prime, bigomega(15) = 2 and omega(15) = 2 are both prime and bigomega(16) = 4 is not prime and omega(16) = 1 is not prime. 14 is the smallest number having this property.
